    "2415552": {
      "title": "Skin ulcers in systemic sclerosis: determinants of presence and predictive factors of healing",
      "abstract": "BACKGROUND ::: Skin ulcers are common vascular complications of systemic sclerosis (SSc). ::: ::: ::: OBJECTIVE ::: The aim of the study was to identify clinical, biologic, and imaging parameters that constitute risk factors for the occurrence and persistence of skin ulcers. ::: ::: ::: METHODS ::: One hundred thirty Italian SSc patients were examined at entry and after 20 months of follow-up. ::: ::: ::: RESULTS ::: The diffuse SSc phenotype with avascular areas on capillaroscopy, thrombophilia, and systemic inflammation as defined by interleukin 6 plasma levels, represented the major risk factors for ulcer development. Infection was associated with a risk of poor or no healing, and cardiopulmonary involvement was a major comorbid factor in patients with ulcers. The presence of infection and avascular areas represented the main determinants for ulcer healing. ::: ::: ::: LIMITATIONS ::: Our data should be confirmed with a longer follow-up period since skin ulcers represent a frequent vascular complication in scleroderma patients. ::: ::: ::: CONCLUSION ::: Aggressive therapies aiming at improving angiogenesis and controlling infection and the course of the disease appear to be crucial to obtain ulcer healing."
    }
  },
  "generator": "fallback_v4"
}